                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18370227-903-offence-1 t18370227-name-1357"></join>Edward Grove</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370227-name-1358" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1358" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1358" type="surname" value="GROVE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1358" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD GROVE</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a clothes-shop in Lower-marsb, Lambeth. I employed the prisoner as a cutter—on the 4th of February I marked eight half-crowns and placed them in the till at six o'clock in the evening—I left, and went to my other shop at No. 60—I came back about ten o'clock, and found one half-crown missing from the till—I went for a constable—I took him round to a tailor's, where the prisoner had gone, in Harriett-street, and found him, and had him searched—I found a shilling on him and 6 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in coppers, but no half-crown.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370227-name-1359" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1359" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1359" type="surname" value="CARTWETGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1359" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN CARTWETGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to the prosecutor. I saw the half-crowns after they were marked, and saw them put into the till—I remained in the shop till half-past nine o'clock, when 1 left for a few minutes—I counted the money at that time—there were eight half-crowns all marked—I then left for about five minutes, and when I came back, one was missing—I went to the house in Harriett-street, and then the prisoner was searched, and 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. was found on him—I had followed him from master's, and he went nowhere else.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Were you aware that your employer had marked money previously? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I never before found any marked money missing—followed you to this place—I then left to inform Mr. Grove of it—about ten minutes had elapsed—you appeared frightened when you saw the constabl—you said you had not taken the half-crown.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370227-name-1360" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1360" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1360" type="surname" value="SENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1360" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN SENNIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I work for Mr. Grove in Harriett-street, where the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183702270202"></xptr>
               <p>prisoner was found. He came there about ten o'clock that evening I should judge—he desired me to fetch some, and he gave me half-a-crown to pay for it—I came back with 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—after returning him the change, he gave me 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. due for washing, and then the other parties came—I changed the money at the Patriot.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> On what business did I come? <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> To have your trowsers mended—my husband said he would not be paid for the trowsers as it was so small a trifle, and then you said you would send for gin.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370227-name-1361" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1361" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1361" type="surname" value="GROVE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1361" type="given" value="ISABELLA"></interp>ISABELLA GROVE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my brother, in Lower Marsh, Lambeth. I was in the shop last, about half-past nine o'clock—I left the shop about ten minutes, and the prisoner was left alone—I left with Mr. Cartwright—I went up stairs, and he went out—I returned in about ten minutes—I then remained all the evening—the prisoner was alone in the shop when I returned—no one entered the shop during the ten minutes that I was up stairs—I was there when Cartwright counted the money at half-past nine o'clock—it was all right.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> When you returned was I in the shop? <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> Yes; I left you in the shop—it was your duty to be outside that night, being Saturday, but you were in the shop—I do not recollect your being sent to the other shop to borrow a coat for a customer—I am aware that you bunt the knee of your trowsers—I saw you attempt to mend them yourself—you went up stairs to do so—you came down in a few minutes, and said you could not do them properly, and went to this woman's husband to get them mended.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370227-name-1362" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1362" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1362" type="surname" value="CARTWRIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370227-name-1362" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN CARTWRIGHT</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I counted the money in the till when the prisoner was up stairs—I did not stop him before he went out, because I was not certain whether it was 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or half-a-crown.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> When you left the shop was not I away? <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> Yes; you were at Sennis's—there was a customer for whom you had to go and borrow a coat—another shopman was there, and attended to the cus<lb></lb>tomer.</p>
